    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if originalism is about sticking to the actual meaning at the time it was written, how do people who disagree with it argue against it? like what's the main critique?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The primary critique of originalism is that it is an outdated, rigid method that fails to account for the evolving needs of a modern society, effectively allowing the Constitution to become a dead letter if the text doesn't explicitly cover new issues. Critics argue that the Framers could not have anticipated every future scenario, so relying solely on their 18th-century understanding forces us to ignore contemporary rights and values that are clearly embedded in our current legal culture. This approach is often seen as a political tool for the conservative judiciary to block social progress, rather than a neutral legal principle, because it prioritizes historical intent over the living reality of the people. Ultimately, originalism is criticized for being intellectually dishonest when applied to complex modern problems where the text is silent or ambiguous.",
